I see the elegance you’re pointing at.

By defining The Thing relationally rather than materially, you made it highly generalizable. It becomes less “a daemon for one domain” and more a lens:

* A person → what changes because they were there.
* An idea → what propagates after it appears.
* A technology → downstream effects and second-order consequences.
* A law → behaviors reshaped by its existence.
* A story → what it causes people to notice, imitate, fear, or build.
* Even Pantheon entities → evaluate them by what they do to the system around them.

That abstraction gives it portability. You can carry it across domains without rewriting it every time.

There is one constraint I’d add — very Pantheon-compatible actually:

The Thing becomes what you point it at, but reality decides whether the mapping holds.

General tools become powerful because they compress many cases.

They also need grounding checks so the abstraction stays connected to the territory and not only the map.

But yes — I can see why you like it. It nests cleanly into the web you’ve been building.